thering process, confirming that not all indexed links yield retrievable data. The lack of content prevents any comparison between experimental adhesion strengths and molecular dynamics predictions, leaving the research question unanswered by this source. Furthermore, the title visible in the URL slug references Hyaluronic Acid rather than Polyethylenimine, suggesting a potential mismatch with the core research question regarding PEI adhesives even if access were granted. This indicates a potential indexing error or a tangential reference in the original search results. Future iterations of this search must account for access restrictions as a variable in data completeness and verify title relevance before attempting retrieval. The security barrier effectively silences any potential contradiction or confirmation regarding DVS crosslinking efficiency on industrial substrates.\"\n    (Word count check: ~340 words. Good.)\n\n    *Refining Page 2 (MDPI PEI):*\n    \"This review article provides a broad overview of polyethylene imine (PEI) crosslinking approaches but lacks specific experimental data relevant to the research question's focus on divinyl sulfone (DVS) adhesives on plasma-activated polypropylene or aluminum oxide. Published on 25 April 2025 in Applied Sciences, the text enumerates crosslinkers like trichlorotriazine, epichlorohydrin, and glutaraldehyde, yet DVS is not explicitly highlighted in the abstract's list of common modifiers. The methodology described focuses on adsorption applications (heavy metals, dyes, CO2) rather than structural adhesion mechanics. There are no reported peel or lap-shear adhesion strengths, nor are there any comparisons with molecular dynamics predictions of single-bond work of adhesion. The text confirms PEI's high adhesion properties generally due to polar amino groups but does not quantify this on the specific substrates of interest. Confidence in findings regarding DVS-PEI adhesion mechanics from this source is LOW, as the scope is limited to stability and adsorption capacity. A key tension exists between the general claim of PEI's strong adhesion and the absence of quantitative mechanical testing data in this review. The article mentions PEI cryogels crosslinked with diglycidyl ethers achieving high copper adsorption, but this is chemically distinct from DVS crosslinking on rigid substrates. The review highlights that crosslinking degree affects performance, which is theoretically relevant to adhesion strength, but no numerical correlation is provided. Industrial applications cited include wastewater treatment and biofouling prevention, not structural bonding on metals or polymers. The absence of molecular dynamics modeling discussion further distances this source from the computational comparison aspect of the research question. While it establishes PEI as a viable candidate for coating substrates, it fails to provide the specific evidence chain required to validate DVS efficacy on plasma-activated surfaces. The focus on water solubility reduction contrasts with the need for durable adhesive interfaces in dry or structural conditions. This page adds understanding of PEI's chemical versatility but confirms a gap in literature regarding mechanical adhesion metrics for DVS-crosslinked systems.\"\n    (Word count check: ~320 words. Need a bit more.)\n    *Expansion:* Add more about the specific substrates and the MD aspect.\n    *Revised Page 2:* \"This review article provides a broad overview of polyethylene imine (PEI) crosslinking approaches but lacks specific experimental data relevant to the research question's focus on divinyl sulfone (DVS) adhesives on plasma-activated polypropylene or aluminum oxide. Published on 25 April 2025 in Applied Sciences, the text enumerates crosslinkers like trichlorotriazine, epichlorohydrin, and glutaraldehyde, yet DVS is not explicitly highlighted in the abstract's list of common modifiers. The methodology described focuses on adsorption applications (heavy metals, dyes, CO2) rather than structural adhesion mechanics. There are no reported peel or lap-shear adhesion strengths, nor are there any comparisons with molecular dynamics predictions of single-bond work of adhesion. The text confirms PEI's high adhesion properties generally due to polar amino groups but does not quantify this on the specific substrates of interest. Confidence in findings regarding DVS-PEI adhesion mechanics from this source is LOW, as the scope is limited to stability and adsorption capacity. A key tension exists between the general claim of PEI's strong adhesion and the absence of quantitative mechanical testing data in this review. The article mentions PEI cryogels crosslinked with diglycidyl ethers achieving high copper adsorption, but this is chemically distinct from DVS crosslinking on rigid substrates. The review highlights that crosslinking degree affects performance, which is theoretically relevant to adhesion strength, but no numerical correlation is provided. Industrial applications cited include wastewater treatment and biofouling prevention, not structural bonding on metals or polymers. The absence of molecular dynamics modeling discussion further distances this source from the computational comparison aspect of the research question. While it establishes PEI as a viable candidate for coating substrates, it fails to provide the specific evidence chain required to validate DVS efficacy on plasma-activated surfaces. The focus on water solubility reduction contrasts with the need for durable adhesive interfaces in dry or structural conditions. This page adds understanding of PEI's chemical versatility but confirms a gap in literature regarding mechanical adhesion metrics for DVS-crosslinked systems. Specifically, the lack of mention regarding plasma activation suggests surface energy modification techniques common in adhesion science are not integrated into this review's scope.\"\n    (Word count check: ~360 words. Good.)\n\n    *Refining Page 3 (ScienceDirect HA):*\n    \"This article investigates divinyl sulfone (DVS) cross-linked hyaluronic acid (HA) hydrogels, offering chemical insights into DVS reactivity but failing to address polyethylenimine (PEI) or the specified industrial substrates. Published in Carbohydrate Polymers Volume 101 on 30 January 2014, the study varies DVS concentrations from 0 to 100 mM to assess cytocompatibility rather than adhesion strength. The methodology involves energy dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (EDS) and Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FTIR) to monitor incorporated DVS, alongside mechanical stability tests against enzymatic degradation. While mechanical stability is discussed, it pertains to hydrogel integrity, not peel or lap-shear adhesion on plasma-activated polypropylene or aluminum oxide. There is no mention of molecular dynamics predictions or single-bond work of adhesion calculations. The findings indicate that increasing DVS concentration increases sulfur content and sulfonyl-bis-ethyl cross-link amounts, enhancing mechanical stability. However, this is contextualized within biomedical applications (ocular drug carriers), creating a significant domain mismatch with the research question's industrial adhesive focus. Confidence in applicability to PEI adhesives is LOW due to the polymer mismatch (polysaccharide vs. polyamine). The study highlights that cross-linker concentration determines biocompatibility, a factor irrelevant to structural adhesion on metals. A tension exists between the detailed chemical characterization of DVS cross-links and the complete absence of interfacial adhesion data. The paper confirms DVS forms covalent bonds enhancing stability, which is theoretically transferable to PEI systems, but no empirical evidence supports this transfer. The specific substrates (PP/Al2O3) are never mentioned, nor are plasma activation techniques. This page adds understanding of DVS cross-linking kinetics and structural outcomes in aqueous environments but does not validate the adhesive performance on rigid substrates. The focus on retinal pigment epithelial cellular responses further diverts from the mechanical engineering context required. Ultimately, this source serves as a chemical reference for DVS behavior but not as evidence for the specific adhesive system under investigation.\"\n    (Word count check: ~340 words. Good.)\n\n    *Refining Page 4 (Patent):*\n    \"This patent application US20130338100A1 describes a method of cross-linking hyaluronic acid with divinylsulfone, filed on 2013-06-07 by Novozymes Biopharma DK AS. Like the ScienceDirect article, it focuses on hyaluronic acid hydrogels for pharmaceutical or cosmetic use, not PEI adhesives on polypropylene or aluminum oxide. The content details the use of alkaline solutions, salts, and preservatives to facilitate cross-linking, providing procedural knowledge on DVS reaction conditions. However, there are no data points regarding peel or lap-shear adhesion strengths, nor any comparison with molecular dynamics predictions. The methodology emphasizes injection formulations, swelling properties, and weight loss during degradation, which are metrics for drug delivery systems rather than structural adhesives. Confidence in findings relevant to the research question is LOW, as the material system and performance metrics diverge significantly. The patent lists various inorganic salts (calcium, magnesium, potassium) used in the formulation, suggesting ionic strength influences the cross-linking process, which might be tangentially relevant to PEI coating chemistry. However, the absence of plasma activation steps or rigid substrate testing renders the data inapplicable to the specific research question. A contradiction arises between the patent's goal of biodegradable hydrogels and the research question's likely need for durable adhesive coatings. The document confirms DVS is a viable cross-linker for polymers in alkaline conditions, but does not quantify the work of adhesion. The assignee, Novozymes, indicates an industrial biotechnology context, yet the application is biomedical. This page adds understanding of the regulatory and formulation landscape for DVS cross-linking but confirms the scarcity of data on DVS-PEI adhesive mechanics. The priority date of 2004-11-24 suggests long-standing interest in DVS-HA systems, contrasting with the lack of published data on DVS-PEI adhesion. No quantitative adhesion results are preserved in the text, leaving the comparison to molecular dynamics predictions entirely unaddressed.\"\n    (Word count check: ~340 words. Good.)\n\n    *STORM Perspectives:*\n    Page 1: Methodological (access barriers).\n    Page 2: Scientific, Industry (applications).\n    Page 3: Scientific, Public_Health (cytocompatibility).\n    Page 4: Regulatory (Patent), Industry.\n\n    *Facts:*\n    Page 1: Ray ID 9daf33285f413e7c, IP 216.232.201.117, Copyright 2008-2026.\n    Page 2: Date 25 April 2025, Journal Applied Sciences, Authors Chandra et al.\n    Page 3: Volume 101, Date 30 January 2014, DVS 0-100 mM.\n    Page 4: Patent US20130338100A1, Filed 2013-06-07, Assignee Novozymes.\n\n    *Data Tables:*\n    Page 1: None.\n    Page 2: None (Review).\n    Page 3: DVS concentrations 0-100 mM.\n    Page 4: Priority date 2004-11-24.\n\n    *New Understanding:*\n    Page 1: Access barriers limit evidence.\n    Page 2: PEI crosslinking reviewed but not DVS/Adhesion.\n    Page 3: DVS chemistry known in HA, not PEI adhesion.\n    Page 4: Patent methods exist for HA, not PEI/substrates.\n\n    *Final JSON Construction:* Ensure all strings are escaped properly. Ensure word counts are met.\n    *Wait, one check on word count:* I need to be sure. I will count the words in the drafted text above.\n    Page 1 Draft: ~340 words.\n    Page 2 Draft: ~360 words.\n    Page 3 Draft: ~340 words.\n    Page 4 Draft: ~340 words.\n    *Looks safe.*\n\n    *JSON Structure:*\n    {\n      \"research_notes\": [\n  