h results, there is no comparative data available regarding the environmental degradation rates or service lifespan of divinyl sulfone (DVS)-crosslinked polyethylenimine (PEI) adhesives versus standard epoxy systems under thermal cycling. While Sources 1 and 6 confirm that linear and branched PEI were crosslinked with DVS to yield rigid and insoluble structures, these studies focused exclusively on CO2 gas adsorption rather than adhesive performance on polypropylene or aluminum oxide substrates. Furthermore, Sources 2, 3, 7, 8, and 10 discuss DVS crosslinking primarily in the context of hyaluronic acid hydrogels for biomedical applications, noting modifications to mechanical properties and degradation rates, but do not address structural adhesive bonding or thermal cycling durability. General adhesive aging is mentioned in Sources 13, 14, and 15, discussing peel strength reduction after artificial aging or humidity exposure, yet none specify DVS-PEI chemistry or compare it to epoxies for total cost of ownership models. Source 9 discusses adhesive bond durability generally but lacks specific chemical comparisons. Consequently, the specific durability differential and its influence on cost models cannot be determined from this literature set. The search results fail to provide experimental evidence linking DVS-PEI coatings to plasma-activated substrates or molecular dynamics predictions of work adhesion. Therefore, no conclusion can be drawn regarding the economic perspective of service lifespan or total cost of ownership differences between these adhesive systems based on the available information. Explicit data on thermal cycling effects and long-term service lifespan comparisons required for economic modeling is absent. This gap prevents any assessment of how durability differentials influence total cost of ownership models for these specific materials.\"\n        (Approx 260 words).\n\n    *   Key Findings need to be 3-5 bullet points.\n    *   Sources Used need t