..\". This is metadata, not body text.\n    *   **Decision:** I must set source_quality to 0.0 and extract ZERO facts for Source 2 because there is no article body text to extract from, only navigation and citation metadata. Extracting facts from the title alone violates the \"ARTICLE BODY TEXT\" rule (titles are metadata).\n    *   **Wait:** Can I extract facts from the title? \"Health Risk Assessment: A Case Study In One of the Adhesives Manufacturing Industries of Alborz Province in 2020\". That is a title. The rule says \"ONLY extract from the ARTICLE BODY TEXT\". Titles are usually considered metadata. The content provided is basically the header/sidebar/footer of the journal page.\n    *   **Conclusion for Source 2:** Source quality 0.0. Zero facts.\n\n4.  **Re-evaluating Source 1 Fact Extraction:**\n    *   I need 8-15 facts.\n    *   Text available: Abstract + partial Introduction.\n    *   Research Question: DVS crosslinked PEI adhesive coatings on plasma-activated PP/Al2O3, adhesion strength vs MD.\n    *   Source 1 Content: PEI crosslinking for adsorption (metals, dyes, CO2). Crosslinkers: trichlorotriazine, epichlorohydrin, etc. Substrates: carbon cloth.\n    *   Relevance: Very low. This source does not answer the RQ. However, I must extract facts from the source if it contains content. I will extract the available facts but score relevance low (0.1-0.3) to indicate it doesn't answer the RQ.\n    *   **Wait, is it better to set Source 1 quality low too?** It is a peer-reviewed journal (Applied Sciences, MDPI), 2025. Quality is high (0.8), but Relevance to RQ is low.\n    *   **Fact Extraction Plan for Source 1:**\n        1.  PEI is synthetic water-soluble nitrogen-rich polymer.\n        2.  PEI exists in linear or branched forms.\n        3.  PEI modified by crosslinking using molecular/polymeric crosslinkers.\n        4.  Crosslinkers include trichlorotriazine, epichlorohydrin, ethylene glycol diglycidyl ether.\n        5.  Crosslinking increases stability and reduces water solubility.\n        6.  PEI has strong affinity for metal cations like Cu2+, Au3+, Pb2+.\n        7.  Nitrogen atoms interact with metal ions.\n        8.  Suitable to remove metals from water with high efficiency.\n        9.  Thin film of crosslinked PEI on substrates can be prepared.\n        10. Applications include removing metals and dyes, biofouling prevention.\n        11. Copper ion can be stored in thin film on carbon cloth substrate.\n        12. Copper released by passing electric current or acid treatment.\n        13. Crosslinked PEI used for adsorption of gases such as CO2 and SO2.\n        14. Performance affected by several factors.\n        15. Success dependent on type of crosslinker and degree of crosslinking.\n        16. Heavy metals are common pollutants presenting major threat to public health.\n        17. Heavy metals enter environment from metal plating, pickling, pigment industries.\n    *   I will select 8-15 of these. I must ensure quotes are >10 words.\n    *   **Quote Check:**\n        *   \"PEI is a synthetic water-soluble and nitrogen-rich polymer with an ethylene amine repeating unit\" (14 words) - OK.\n        *   \"It exists in a linear or branched forms and finds applications in various areas\" (13 words) - OK.\n        *   \"PEI is often chemically modified by crosslinking reactions using molecular and polymeric crosslinkers\" (13 words) - OK.\n        *   \"trichlorotriazine, epichlorohydrin, ethylene glycol diglycidyl ether, poly(ethylene glycol) diglycidyl ether, etc.\" (12 words) - OK.\n        *   \"to increase its stability and reduce its water solubility\" (10 words) - OK.\n        *   \"PEI (pristine/crosslinked) has a strong affinity for metal cations (e.g., Cu2+, Au3+, Pb2+, etc.)\" (14 words) - OK.\n        *   \"where the nitrogen atoms interact with the metal ions, and hence is suitable to remove metals\" (15 words) - OK.\n        *   \"A thin film of crosslinked PEI on substrates can be prepared and finds diverse applications\" (14 words) - OK.\n        *   \"such as in removing metals and dyes, and biofouling prevention in the marine environment\" (13 words) - OK.\n        *   \"The copper ion, as an example, can be stored (adsorbed) in a thin film of crosslinked PEI\" (16 words) - OK.\n        *   \"on a carbon cloth substrate, which can be released to water by passing an electric current\" (15 words) - OK.\n        *   \"It has also been reported that crosslinked PEI and composite materials can be used for the adsorption\" (15 words) - OK.\n        *   \"of dyes and gases such as CO2 and SO2 from the environment\" (12 words) - OK.\n        *   \"The performance of pristine/composite/crosslinked PEI in gas, metal ion, and dye adsorption is affected\" (14 words) - OK.\n        *   \"by several factors. Studies have shown that the properties of the crosslinked PEI and hence its success\" (15 words) - OK.\n        *   \"in capturing metal ions, dyes, and CO2 is dependent not only on the type of crosslinker\" (14 words) - OK.\n        *   \"but also on the degree of crosslinking. Heavy metals are common pollutants in the environment\" (13 words) - OK.\n        *   \"that present a major threat to public health, even at trace levels.\" (12 words) - OK.\n        *   \"Heavy metals enter the environment from different sources, which include metal plating, pickling, pigment industries\" (14 words) - OK.\n\n    *   I have enough facts. I will select the top 10-12 most specific ones to ensure quality over quantity, but the prompt asks for 8-15. I will aim for 10 to be safe on quality.\n    *   **Relevance Scoring:** Since none of these answer the RQ (DVS, plasma-PP, adhesion strength), the relevance scores must be low (0.1-0.4). I will distribute them uniquely as required.\n    *   **Perspective:** Scientific.\n\n5.  **Re-evaluating Source 2:**\n    *   Content is purely navigation and metadata. No abstract, no body.\n    *   Rule: \"If the source is mostly 